{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503143"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1934"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1934"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.12,0.04,0.09,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1934"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59030"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1934"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1934"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44441"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18377"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59030"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to a regional Emergency Department after hours with a four-hour history of sharp lower abdominal pain. The is no current access to ultrasound scan services without calling in a sonographer but there is access to after-hours CT. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pain came on gradually whilst she was out walking, is constant in nature and is worse in the left side of her abdomen. She has no other symptoms. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She has a regular 28-day menstrual cycle with four days of bleeding requiring up to five pads on the heaviest day. Her last menstrual period was two weeks ago. She has been with her current partner for 12 months and uses condoms regularly. She also notes an increase in vaginal discharge over the past two days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft, apart from mild tenderness to deep palpation in the left iliac fossa. There are no peritoneal signs. Her full blood count and serum biochemistry are within normal limits. The CRP is \u003C5 and the serum bHCG is \u003C2 IU/L (\u003C5). Paracetamol 1 g and Ibuprofen 400mg are provided to the patient in the Emergency Department with some effect. Her pain is now settling. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit as an inpatient for transvaginal ultrasound in the morning","CT pelvis to be done urgently","Admit as an inpatient for diagnostic laparoscopy","Admit for observation and analgesia","Discharge with NSAIDs and organise an outpatient pelvic USS"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute unilateral pelvic pain two weeks after her last menstrual period, which is highly suggestive of mittelschmerz (ovulation pain). Given that she is clinically well, has normal vital signs and blood tests, and her pain is improving with simple analgesia, conservative outpatient management is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge with NSAIDs and organise an outpatient pelvic USS\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. While the pain is likely mittelschmerz, which is self-limiting, an outpatient ultrasound is reasonable to exclude other pathology such as ovarian cysts or endometriosis. NSAIDs are effective for managing the pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmission as an inpatient for transvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were concerns about ovarian torsion or ruptured cyst. However, the gradual onset, absence of severe pain or vomiting, and improvement with analgesia make these diagnoses unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the first-line imaging modality for gynecological conditions. Ultrasound provides better visualization of pelvic organs without radiation exposure. CT would be considered if there were concerns about appendicitis or other acute surgical conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmission for diagnostic laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive given the patient\u0027s clinical stability and likely benign diagnosis. Laparoscopy would be considered if symptoms were severe, persistent, or if there was strong suspicion of endometriosis after failed medical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmission for observation and analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary given that the patient is clinically stable, her pain is improving with oral analgesia, and there are no red flags suggesting serious pathology. She can be safely managed as an outpatient with clear instructions to return if symptoms worsen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In patients with abdominal pain who are clinically well with a normal bHCG, benign causes of pelvic pain such as mittelschmerz should be considered."],"references":["Management of suspected ovarian masses in the premenopausal woman (Green-top Guideline No. 62). In: RCOG [online]. 2011 [Accessed 2020 Aug 28]. Available at: https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/gtg_62.pdf.","Bottomley C, Bourne T. Diagnosis and management of ovarian cyst accidents. Best Pract Res Clin Obstet Gynaecol. 2009 Oct;23(5):711-24. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19299205/","Durai R, Ng PC. Mittelschmerz mimicking appendicitis. Br J Hosp Med (Lond). 2009 Jul;70(7):419. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19584789/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44441"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1934"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44441"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-04T13:58:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-04T14:02:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1934"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59030"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"g